.TH READSEEK 1 "2026-06-28" "readseek 0.4.25" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
readseek \- structural source-code reader with stable line hashing
.SH SYNOPSIS
.nf
\fBreadseek\fR [\fB\-h\fR|\fB--help\fR]
\fBreadseek\fR [\fB\-V\fR|\fB--version\fR]
\fBreadseek\fR [\fB--readseek-dir\fR \fIdir\fR] \fIcommand\fR ...

\fBreadseek detect\fR [\fB--language\fR \fIlanguage\fR]
    [\fB--transcribe\fR] [\fB--caption\fR] [\fB--objects\fR]
    (\fB--stdin\fR \fIpath\fR | \fItarget\fR)

\fBreadseek read\fR [\fB--language\fR \fIlanguage\fR]
    [\fB--start\fR \fIline\fR]
    [\fB--end\fR \fIline\fR|\fB--limit\fR \fIn\fR]
    (\fB--stdin\fR \fIpath\fR | \fItarget\fR)

\fBreadseek map\fR [\fB--language\fR \fIlanguage\fR]
    (\fB--stdin\fR \fIpath\fR | \fItarget\fR)

\fBreadseek check\fR [\fB--language\fR \fIlanguage\fR]
    (\fB--stdin\fR \fIpath\fR | \fItarget\fR)

\fBreadseek symbol\fR [\fB--language\fR \fIlanguage\fR] [\fB--line\fR \fIline\fR]
    (\fB--stdin\fR \fIpath\fR | \fItarget\fR) [\fB--name\fR \fIqualified-name\fR]

\fBreadseek identify\fR [\fB--language\fR \fIlanguage\fR]
    [\fB--line\fR \fIline\fR] [\fB--column\fR \fIcolumn\fR]
    (\fB--stdin\fR \fIpath\fR | \fItarget\fR)

\fBreadseek def\fR [\fB--from-identify\fR] [\fB--format\fR \fIformat\fR] [\fB\-c\fR|\fB--cached\fR] [\fB\-o\fR|\fB--others\fR]
    [\fB\-i\fR|\fB--ignored\fR] [\fB--language\fR \fIlanguage\fR]
    \fItarget\fR [\fIname\fR]

\fBreadseek refs\fR [\fB--format\fR \fIformat\fR] [\fB--scope\fR \fB--line\fR \fIline\fR [\fB--column\fR \fIcolumn\fR]]
    [\fB\-c\fR|\fB--cached\fR] [\fB\-o\fR|\fB--others\fR]
    [\fB\-i\fR|\fB--ignored\fR] [\fB--language\fR \fIlanguage\fR]
    \fItarget\fR \fIname\fR

\fBreadseek rename\fR \fB--line\fR \fIline\fR [\fB--column\fR \fIcolumn\fR] \fB--to\fR \fIname\fR
    [\fB--workspace\fR \fIdir\fR] [\fB\-c\fR|\fB--cached\fR] [\fB\-o\fR|\fB--others\fR]
    [\fB\-i\fR|\fB--ignored\fR] [\fB--apply\fR] [\fB--language\fR \fIlanguage\fR] \fItarget\fR

\fBreadseek search\fR [\fB\-c\fR|\fB--cached\fR] [\fB\-o\fR|\fB--others\fR]
    [\fB\-i\fR|\fB--ignored\fR] [\fB--language\fR \fIlanguage\fR]
    \fItarget\fR \fIpattern\fR

\fBreadseek init\fR [\fIpath\fR]
.fi
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B readseek
is a command-line tool that reads source files and outputs pretty-printed JSON.
It is designed for scripts, editors, and coding agents that need stable addressable
source context.

Every output line carries a \fIhashline\fR: a line number, a short 3-character hash,
and the original text. These hashes are stable anchors that let subsequent calls
refer back to specific lines without depending on shifting line numbers.

Diagnostics and errors are written separately from JSON output, making the tool
safe to pipe into other programs.

.SH INPUTS AND TARGETS

Most commands take a file or directory \fItarget\fR on the command line.
The \fBdetect\fR, \fBread\fR, \fBmap\fR, \fBcheck\fR, \fBsymbol\fR, and \fBidentify\fR
commands can alternatively read from standard input with \fB--stdin\fR \fIpath\fR, where
\fIpath\fR supplies a filename used for language detection and output metadata.
You cannot combine \fB--stdin\fR with a positional target.

A target path may carry a suffix that selects a specific line:
.nf
.RS
\fIfile\fR:\fIline\fR
\fIfile\fR:\fIhash\fR
.RE
.fi
Line numbers are one-based. A hash suffix is a 3-character string that was
previously emitted by \fBread\fR, \fBmap\fR, or \fBsearch\fR output.

For \fBsymbol\fR, you can also pass \fB--name\fR with a qualified or unqualified
symbol name. If the name matches more than one symbol the command reports an error.

For \fBdef\fR, the \fB--from-identify\fR flag reads a JSON object previously produced
by \fBidentify\fR. The lookup tries \fIsymbol.qualified_name\fR first and falls
back to \fIidentifier.text\fR.

.SH LANGUAGES

.B readseek
detects the language from the file name, extension, shebang line, and syntax hints.
Pass \fB--language\fR when detection is ambiguous, when input comes from a synthetic
path, or when a file has no meaningful extension.

The following language identifiers are accepted:
\fBassembly\fR,
\fBbash\fR,
\fBc\fR,
\fBcpp\fR,
\fBcsharp\fR,
\fBcss\fR,
\fBdockerfile\fR,
\fBgdscript\fR,
\fBgo\fR,
\fBhtml\fR,
\fBjava\fR,
\fBjavascript\fR,
\fBjson\fR,
\fBjsx\fR,
\fBjust\fR,
\fBkconfig\fR,
\fBlatex\fR,
\fBlua\fR,
\fBmake\fR,
\fBmarkdown\fR,
\fBmeson\fR,
\fBnix\fR,
\fBperl\fR,
\fBphp\fR,
\fBpuppet\fR,
\fBpython\fR,
\fBriscv\fR,
\fBruby\fR,
\fBrust\fR,
\fBsql\fR,
\fBswift\fR,
\fBtoml\fR,
\fBtsx\fR,
\fBtypescript\fR,
\fBtypst\fR,
\fBxml\fR,
\fByaml\fR,
\fBvimscript\fR, and
\fBzig\fR.
The special value \fBunknown\fR treats the input as plain text and disables any
parser-based features.

.SH COMMANDS
.TP
.B detect
Print detection metadata for the input as a JSON object. The \fBtype\fR field
contains the exact MIME type detected by inspecting the file content, or
\fBtext/plain\fR as a fallback. Source files include the detected language, parser
engine, support flag, optional MIME type, and optional syntax name. Image files
also include format, width, height, and animation status. With
\fB--transcribe\fR, \fB--caption\fR, or \fB--objects\fR the image is analyzed with
the Qwen3-VL vision model (downloaded to the user cache directory on first use): \fB--transcribe\fR adds a \fItranscribe\fR object
with the recognized \fItext\fR and per-region bounding quads, \fB--caption\fR adds
a \fIcaption\fR string, and \fB--objects\fR adds an \fIobjects\fR array of category
labels with bounding boxes.
.TP
.B read
Print line numbers, hashes, and text for a range of lines. Without any range
options the entire file is returned. Use a line or hash suffix on the target
path, or pass \fB--start\fR, to set the first line.
Use \fB--end\fR for the last line (inclusive) or \fB--limit\fR for a count;
the two cannot be combined.
.TP
.B map
Print the structural source map: each top-level symbol's kind, name, qualified
name, start and end line, boundary hashes, the symbol's \fIstart_byte\fR and
\fIend_byte\fR span, and the \fIname_byte\fR offset of its name token. For languages
that do not support symbol extraction the output contains an empty symbol list.
.TP
.B check
Print parse diagnostics: the counts of tree-sitter \fIERROR\fR and \fIMISSING\fR
nodes and a list of each diagnostic's kind and start and end line. For languages
without a tree-sitter parser the output contains zero counts and an empty list.
.TP
.B symbol
Print the source range for one symbol. Pick it by \fB--name\fR (qualified or
unqualified) or by \fB--line\fR. When only \fB--line\fR is given, the symbol
that contains that line is resolved.
.TP
.B identify
Print the requested cursor line, its hash, the identifier at the cursor position,
and the enclosing mapped symbol. If \fB--column\fR is omitted, column 1 is used.
Columns are one-based byte offsets and must be within the selected line. The
identifier token is resolved with the language parser when available, falling
back to an ASCII identifier scan otherwise. Identifier ranges in the JSON use a
one-based inclusive start column and a one-based exclusive end column, plus
\fIstart_byte\fR and \fIend_byte\fR file offsets that mark the exact token span.
.TP
.B def
Find definitions of a mapped symbol in a file or directory. The \fIname\fR argument
matches a fully qualified or unqualified symbol name. With \fB--from-identify\fR and no
\fIname\fR, the name is read from an \fBidentify\fR JSON object on standard input.
Directory search follows the same file-selection rules as \fBsearch\fR.
Use \fB--format plain\fR to emit quickfix-friendly location entries instead of full
definition objects.
.TP
.B refs
Find all occurrences of an identifier in a file or directory. Output is a flat
list of locations with file, line, column, line hash, line text, and the enclosing
symbol when available. Directory search rules are the same as for \fBsearch\fR.
Use \fB--format plain\fR to flatten symbol metadata into each location entry.

With \fB--scope\fR and \fB--line\fR/\fB--column\fR, resolution is restricted to the
lexical binding under the cursor within a single file. Each reported location then
carries an \fIoccurrence\fR field of \fBdefinition\fR or \fBreference\fR, and
same-named occurrences that resolve to a different binding are excluded. Scope
resolution is currently available for \fBrust\fR, \fBc\fR, and \fBcpp\fR; other
languages report no resolvable binding.
.TP
.B rename
Plan a binding-accurate rename of the lexical binding under \fB--line\fR/\fB--column\fR
within a single file. The output is an edit plan: \fIold_name\fR, \fInew_name\fR,
any \fIconflicts\fR the new name would introduce, and an \fIedits\fR array with the
line, column range, byte range, occurrence kind, and the line hashline for each
edit. Without \fB--apply\fR the command does not modify files; it emits the plan for
a caller to apply. With \fB--apply\fR the edits are written to the file, but only
after refusing on any conflict and re-verifying that every edited line's hash still
matches the plan, so a file that changed since planning is rejected rather than
corrupted. The reported \fIapplied\fR field indicates whether the file was written.
Rename uses the same scope resolution as \fBrefs --scope\fR and is available for the
same languages.
.IP
With \fB--workspace\fR the rename expands across the given directory or repository.
The cursor file stays binding-accurate; every other file is matched by name, the
same way \fBrefs\fR matches, and the additional files appear in an \fIothers\fR array
of per-file plans. Because readseek has no cross-file symbol resolver, an occurrence
in another file is renamed only when it does not resolve to a local declaration
there, so a same-named local binding is left untouched; files in languages without
binding support are matched by name alone. Directory selection honours the same
\fB\-c\fR/\fB\-o\fR/\fB\-i\fR Git flags as \fBrefs\fR. With \fB--apply\fR every file is
verified first and only written if all pass, so a conflict or hash drift in any file
aborts the whole rename without leaving a partial result.
.TP
.B search
Run an AST pattern against a file or every supported source file under a directory.
Files that cannot be parsed or are in unsupported languages are skipped.
Pattern variables use \fB$\fR\fINAME\fR to match a single node and
\fB$$$\fR\fINAME\fR to match zero or more sibling nodes.
Output is grouped by file and includes the file hash, matched ranges, captures,
boundary hashes, and hashlines for each match.
.TP
.B init
Initialize a \fI.readseek/\fR directory under \fIpath\fR (defaults to the current
directory). This directory holds the source-map cache used by other commands.
If the \fI.readseek/\fR directory already exists, \fBinit\fR reinitializes it.
readseek also refreshes the cache internally on each invocation.

.SH OPTIONS
.TP
\fB\-h\fR, \fB--help\fR
Print usage information and exit.
.TP
\fB\-V\fR, \fB--version\fR
Print the program version and exit.
.TP
\fB--readseek-dir\fR \fIdir\fR
Use \fIdir\fR as the \fI.readseek/\fR directory instead of discovering one by
walking up from the target, analogous to \fBgit\fR's \fB--git-dir\fR. This global
option must precede the command. For \fBinit\fR it controls where the directory is
created; other commands read and refresh their source-map cache there.
.TP
\fB--language\fR \fIlanguage\fR
Force a specific language instead of auto-detection. See \fBLANGUAGES\fR above.
.TP
\fB--stdin\fR \fIpath\fR
Read document contents from standard input instead of a file, using \fIpath\fR
for language detection and reported in JSON output.
.TP
\fB--from-identify\fR
For \fBdef\fR, read an \fBidentify\fR JSON object from standard input and use it
to choose the symbol name instead of passing \fIname\fR.
.TP
\fB--format\fR \fIformat\fR
For \fBdef\fR and \fBrefs\fR, select the output format: \fIjson\fR (default) for
the command-specific JSON shape, or \fIplain\fR for flat \fIlocations\fR arrays
with editor-friendly fields.
.TP
\fB--line\fR \fIline\fR
One-based target line for \fBsymbol\fR or \fBidentify\fR, or the cursor line for
\fBrefs --scope\fR and \fBrename\fR.
.TP
\fB--column\fR \fIcolumn\fR
One-based byte column for \fBidentify\fR or the cursor column for \fBrefs --scope\fR
and \fBrename\fR.
Identifier ranges in JSON use a one-based inclusive start column and a one-based
exclusive end column.
.TP
\fB--scope\fR
For \fBrefs\fR, resolve only the lexical binding under \fB--line\fR/\fB--column\fR
in a single file instead of matching every occurrence of the name.
.TP
\fB--to\fR \fIname\fR
For \fBrename\fR, the new name for the binding. Must be a plain identifier and
differ from the current name.
.TP
\fB--workspace\fR \fIdir\fR
For \fBrename\fR, expand the rename across the directory or repository \fIdir\fR.
The cursor file stays binding-accurate; other files are matched by name (local
shadows excluded) and returned in an \fIothers\fR array. Honours the
\fB\-c\fR/\fB\-o\fR/\fB\-i\fR Git flags.
.TP
\fB--apply\fR
For \fBrename\fR, write the planned edits. Refuses on any naming conflict and
verifies each edited line's hash before writing. With \fB--workspace\fR every file
is verified first and written all-or-nothing.
.TP
\fB--start\fR \fIline\fR
First line to include when reading. If the target path also carries a line
suffix, the two must agree.
.TP
\fB--end\fR \fIline\fR
Last line to include when reading. Cannot be combined with \fB--limit\fR.
.TP
\fB--limit\fR \fIn\fR
Maximum number of lines to include when reading. Cannot be combined with \fB--end\fR.
.TP
\fB\-c\fR, \fB--cached\fR
When searching a directory inside a Git repository, or expanding \fBrename
--workspace\fR, search tracked and indexed files.
.TP
\fB\-o\fR, \fB--others\fR
When searching a directory inside a Git repository, or expanding \fBrename
--workspace\fR, search untracked files that are not ignored.
.TP
\fB\-i\fR, \fB--ignored\fR
With \fB--others\fR, also include ignored untracked files. Inside a Git repository
\fB--ignored\fR requires \fB--others\fR.

.SH DIRECTORY SEARCH

The \fBdef\fR, \fBrefs\fR, and \fBsearch\fR commands accept either
a single file or a directory. A file is searched as-is; a directory is searched
recursively.

Inside a Git work tree, directory searches are Git-aware. Without any selection
flags, \fBreadseek\fR searches both tracked/indexed files and untracked,
non-ignored files. Pass \fB--cached\fR or \fB--others\fR to restrict to one group.
Outside a Git work tree the selection flags are ignored and a normal recursive
walk is used.

.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
.B 0
Success.
.TP
.B 1
Operational error: file not found, binary input, malformed input, cache failure,
or symbol lookup failure.
.TP
.B 2
Usage error: incorrect invocation or argument combination.

.SH FILES
.TP
.I .readseek/maps/
Binary source-map cache files keyed by file hash.
.TP
.I .readseek/def-index/
Sharded JSON definition index used by \fBdef\fR directory lookup.
.TP
.I .readseek/def-index.json
Legacy definition index removed during cache refresh when present.
.TP
.I $XDG_CACHE_HOME/readseek/qwen3-vl-2b/
Qwen3-VL vision model files (GGUF and multimodal projection), downloaded
lazily on first use of \fB--transcribe\fR, \fB--caption\fR, or \fB--objects\fR.

.SH EXAMPLES

Detect the language of a file:
.EX
readseek detect src/main.rs
.EE

Read lines 10 through 20:
.EX
readseek read src/main.rs --start 10 --end 20
.EE

Read 12 lines starting from line 42:
.EX
readseek read src/main.rs:42 --limit 12
.EE

Read unsaved buffer text from standard input:
.EX
printf '%s\\n' 'fn main() {}' | readseek read --stdin scratch.rs
.EE

Build a structural map of a file:
.EX
readseek map src/main.rs
.EE

Look up a symbol by name or by the line it's on:
.EX
readseek symbol src/main.rs --name run
readseek symbol src/main.rs:270
.EE

Identify what's under the cursor at line 42, column 8:
.EX
readseek identify src/main.rs:42 --column 8
.EE

Find definitions of a symbol in tracked files:
.EX
readseek def -c src run --language rust
.EE

Find references to a symbol in tracked files:
.EX
readseek refs -c src main --language rust
.EE

Search Rust functions with an AST pattern:
.EX
readseek search -c src 'fn $NAME() { $$$BODY }' --language rust
.EE

Plan a rename of the binding under the cursor:
.EX
readseek rename src/main.rs --line 42 --column 8 --to renamed
.EE

Apply the rename to the file:
.EX
readseek rename src/main.rs --line 42 --column 8 --to renamed --apply
.EE

Rename a symbol across the repository (cursor file binding-accurate, other files
matched by name) and apply it all-or-nothing:
.EX
readseek rename src/main.rs --line 42 --column 8 --to renamed --workspace . --apply
.EE

.SH BUILDING

Build from source:
.EX
cargo build --release
.EE
The included Makefile also provides install and uninstall targets.

